<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="603" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="6.[1970,2566,1045,1468]" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1970,2126,1045,1074]" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="W. N. Verheyen et al., 2011" authorityName="W. N. Verheyen" authorityYear="2011" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="muzei">Acomys muzei W. N. Verheyen et al., 2011</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation box="[2106,2358,1089,1114]" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">“Muze, Tanzania.”</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="603" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[1970,2566,1045,1468]" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">
<taxonomicName box="[1971,2064,1120,1154]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Acomys</taxonomicName>
muzer was recently described molecularly and morphometrically and was sorted from the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1852" box="[2229,2448,1202,1231]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spinosissimus">A. spinosissimus</taxonomicName>
species complex. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="603" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" startId="6.[1971,2139,1286,1311]" targetBox="[1356,1948,1049,1464]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[1970,2566,1045,1468]" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1971,2143,1286,1311]" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from Tanzania, recorded from Lake Victoria S to hills close to Lake Rukwa and W Eastern Arc Mts.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="603" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[1970,2566,1045,1468]" lastBlockId="6.[1358,2566,1474,2139]" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1971,2221,1395,1429]" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 75-97 mm, tail 79-103 mm, ear 12-15 mm, hindfoot 15-17 mm; weight 14-24 g. The Muze Spiny Mouse has the same external morphological characteristics as the Southern African Spiny Mouse (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1852" box="[2217,2428,1514,1548]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spinosissimus">A. spinosissimus</taxonomicName>
) and can only be distinguished with detailed morphometric or molecular analysis. Tail length is equal to head-body length. Chromosomal complement is 2n = 58-62 and FN = 68-76.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="603" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[1358,2566,1474,2139]" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1359,1470,1632,1666]" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">Habitat.</emphasis>
Woodlands and wooded grasslands, dry miombo (
<taxonomicName box="[2236,2397,1632,1666]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Brachystegia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Brachystegia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[2420,2550,1632,1666]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
) woodland with open canopy, and close to wetlands dominated by acacia (
<taxonomicName box="[2416,2506,1671,1705]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Acacia</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
), elephant grass (Pennisetum purpureum, 
<taxonomicName box="[2031,2151,1711,1745]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[2182,2444,1711,1745]" class="Liliopsida" family="Typhaceae" genus="Typha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Typhaceae">Typha (Typhaceae)</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Cyperus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Cyperaceae">Cyperus (Cyperaceae)</taxonomicName>
. Associated areas, perhaps occupied by the Muze Spiny Mice, are also used for maize and paddy farming.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
